
Syntax for Mysql:-

A> Syntax for Databases:-
1. CREATE DATABASE {database_name};     
2. USE {database_name};                     
3. DROP DATABASE {database_name};            
4. RENAME DATABASE {old_name} TO {new_name};
5. ALTER DATABASE {database_name} READ ONLY = 0/1;  # 0=OFF, 1=ON


B> Syntax for Tables:-
1. CREATE TABLE {table_name} (
  {column_name1} {datatype},
  {column_name2} {datatype},
  ...... );
2. RENAME TABLE {old_name} TO {new_name};
3. DROP TABLE {table_name};
4. DELETE * FROM TABLE {table_name} or TRUNCATE TABLE {table_name};


C> Syntax for Columns:-
1. ALTER TABLE {table_name} 
   ADD {column_name} {datatype};

2. ALTER TABLE {table_name} 
   DROP COLUMN {column_name};

3. ALTER TABLE {table_name} 
   MODIFY {column_name} {new_datatype};

4. ALTER TABLE {table_name} 
   RENAME COLUMN {old_name} TO {new_name};

5. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
   MODIFY {column_name} {datatype}
   AFTER {column_name};

6. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
   MODIFY {column_name} {datatype}
   FIRST;


D> Datatypes in MySQL:-
There are 3 categories of datatypes in SQL :- 
String, numeric and data & time  
Most commonly used datatypes are as follows:-
-> String : VARCHAR(size), CHAR, TEXT, ENUM
-> Numeric : INT(size), DECIMAL(size, decimal places)
-> Date & Time : DATE, DATETIME(fsp), TIMESTAMP(fsp), TIME(fsp), YEAR


E> Constraints:-
There are 8 constraints in SQL, here is a list of all of them:-
1 NOT NULL
2 UNIQUE
3 PRIMARY KEY
4 FOREIGN KEY
5 CHECK
6 DEFAULT
7 AUTO_INCREMENT
8 INDEX or CREATE INDEX

1. CREATE TABLE {table_name} (
    {column_name1} {datatype} {constraint},
    {column_name2} {datatype} {constraint},
    {column_name3} {datatype} {constraint},
    ....);
---> The following constraints are commonly used in SQL:
UNIQUE - Ensures that all values in a column are different
2. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
   ADD CONSTRAINT
   UNIQUE({column_name});
NOT NULL - Ensures that a column cannot have a NULL value
3. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
   MODIFY {column_name} {datatype} NOT NULL;
CHECK - Ensures that the values in a column satisfies a specific condition
DEFAULT - Sets a default value for a column if no value is specified
5. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
ALTER {column_name} SET DEFAULT {data}
PRIMARY KEY - A combination of a NOT NULL and UNIQUE. Uniquely identifies each row in a table
6. ALTER TABLE {table_name}
   ADD CONSTRAINT
   PRIMARY KEY({column_name});
FOREIGN KEY - Prevents actions that would destroy links between tables
AUTO INCREMENT - Used to create and retrieve data from the database very quickly


F> Inserting data into tables:-
1. INSERT INTO (table_name}
   VALUE ({column_data1}, {column_data2}, {column_data3}, .....), 
2. INSERT INTO {table_name}
   VALUES ({column_data1}, {column_data2}, {column_data3}, .....), 
   ({column_data1}, {column_data2}, {column_data3}, .....), 
   ({column_data1}, {column_data2}, {column_data3}, .....), 
    .....;
3. INSERT INTO {table_name} ({column_name1, column_name2)
   VALUES ({column_data1}, {column_data2}, .....);

G> Autocommit, commit & rollback
1. SET AUTOCOMMIT = ON/OFF;
2. COMMIT;
3. ROLLBACK;
